Boil a large #pot of @water{to taste}(salted) for the rice.

Add the @jasmine rice{150%g} and cook for ~{12-15%mins}.

Drain in a #sieve and pop back in the pot.

Cover with a #lid and leave to the side until ready to serve.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}.

Halve the @bell pepper{1}, remove the core and seeds and thinly slice.

Trim and thinly slice the @pak choi{1} widthways.

Peel and finely grate the @ginger{1}(peeled).

Roughly chop the @coriander{5%g}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Place a medium #pan over a medium-high heat (no oil).

Once the pan is hot, add the @Irish beef mince{250%g} and fry until browned, ~{5-6%mins}. Use a #spoon to break it up as it cooks.

  Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the onion and pepper to the pan with a drizzle of @oil{to taste} if necessary.

Cook until softened, ~{4-5%mins}, stirring occasionally.

Add the @Thai style spice mix{1%sachet} and ginger and fry for ~{1%min} then add the @chicken stock{1%sachet} along with @water{100%ml} (double for 4p).

Stir in the pak choi. Simmer until the liquid has reduced by half and the pak choi is tender, ~{3-4%mins}.

While everything cooks, zest and halve the @lime{1}.

When the sauce has reduced, stir through the @ketjap manis{1%sachet}, a squeeze of lime juice and half the coriander.

Remove from the heat, and season to taste with salt and pepper.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork and stir through the lime zest.

Share the rice between #bowls and serve the beef on top.

Finish with a sprinkle of the remaining coriander.

Chop any remaining lime into wedges and serve alongside.